Here's the full migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that don't exist in modern .NET:

## Pattern Inventory

| Pattern | Location | Issue |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Calls `Thread.Abort` internally → `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` (×3) | `endResponse: true` triggers `Thread.Abort` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | No longer thrown; dead code in .NET 8 |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // ASP.NET Core: return IActionResult instead of writing to Response directly.
    // The framework handles Content-Disposition, content type, and flushing.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — return a FileResult instead.
        // The framework writes headers and body, then completes the response.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect without endResponse — just return a 302 result.
            // No Thread.Abort, no exception, no catch block needed.
            return RedirectPermanent("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch is gone — it is never thrown in .NET 8.
        // If ProcessRequest uses CancellationToken, catch OperationCanceledException
        // only if you need to handle mid-request cancellation explicitly.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

**1. `Response.End()` → return `FileResult`**
In ASP.NET Core, action methods return results — the framework owns the response lifecycle. `Response.End()` doesn't exist. Returning `File(...)` sets headers and streams the body cleanly.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → return `Redirect(url)`**
The `endResponse: true` parameter existed solely to abort the thread and prevent further response writes. In ASP.NET Core, returning `RedirectResult` ends the action method normally — no abort needed.

**3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed**
This catch block was "expected" in Framework because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw it by design. In .NET 8, `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown. The block is dead code — remove it.

## Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Code after `return` in the old handler** | In Framework, `Response.End()` aborted execution mid-method. In Core, you must `return` the result — any code after it still runs unless you return. |
| **`User.Identity` may be `null`** | ASP.NET Core doesn't guarantee a non-null `Identity`. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the null-conditional pattern. |
| **`Response.Write` in middleware/filters** | If other code writes to `Response.Body` directly, ensure it doesn't also return an `IActionResult` — that causes `InvalidOperationException` (response already started). |
| **Long-running `ProcessRequest`** | If it does heavy work, accept `HttpContext.RequestAborted` (`CancellationToken`) so the server can cancel if the client disconnects. |
| **`catch (Exception)` swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | If `ProcessRequest` honors a `CancellationToken`, `OperationCanceledException` will propagate through your catch-all. Let it bubble up or filter it explicitly. |

### Optional: Making `ProcessRequest` cancellation-aware

```csharp
private void ProcessRequest(CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
{
    // Check at safe points in long-running work
    cancellationToken.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    // ... do work ...
}

// In the action method:
ProcessRequest(HttpContext.RequestAborted);
```

This replaces the old "abort the thread on disconnect" behavior with cooperative cancellation — the only model supported in .NET 8.
